          "body": "The dietary laws occupy the chapter's largest section and have generated the most interpretive debate across the history of biblical scholarship. Three primary theories have been offered for the basis of the clean/unclean distinction: (1) the hygienic theory (forbidden animals were medically dangerous) — rejected by most scholars because it is not the text's own rationale; (2) the symbolic theory (Mary Douglas, *Purity and Danger*, 1966) — unclean animals are those that do not fit their taxonomic category cleanly, symbolizing the wholeness God requires of His people; (3) the identity-separation theory — the dietary laws function primarily to separate Israel from the nations at the most intimate level of daily life, the meal table. The text's own rationale, stated in verse 2 (holy people, chosen possession) and restated in verse 21 (holy people again), strongly favors the third reading, though Douglas's symbolic insight has merit as a complement. The two-condition rule for land animals (split hoof AND cud-chewing, v. 6) — which disqualifies the camel, rabbit, shaphan, and pig for having only one marker — is less a medical regulation than a reminder that holiness requires full compliance, not partial correspondence. The pig (*chazir*, v. 8) is conspicuous in its prominence — it met one criterion (divided hoof) but not the other (cud-chewing), and its prohibition became in the Second Temple period a marker of Jewish identity under Hellenistic pressure (2 Maccabees 6:18; 7:1). The bird section (vv. 11-20) does not state a governing criterion but gives a list of forbidden species, most of which are birds of prey or carrion-feeders — creatures that live by death. Their exclusion reinforces the pattern: the holy people do not eat from the domain of death."
