          "title": "The kid in its mother's milk — holiness at the boundary (14:21)",
          "body": "Verse 21 closes the dietary section with two edge-case laws joined by the holiness formula. The first allows Israel to give a carcass (an animal that died of itself, *nevelah*) to the resident alien or sell it to a foreigner — the dietary restriction is a marker of covenant status, not a universal humanitarian prohibition. The second is the enigmatic 'you shall not boil a young goat in its mother's milk,' which appears identically in Exodus 23:19 and 34:26. Three interpretations have been offered: (1) it is a prohibition against a Canaanite ritual practice (Ugaritic texts were once thought to reference this, but the evidence is disputed); (2) it is a humanitarian law protecting against a cruel confusion of nurture and death; (3) it is a symbol of the separation Israel must maintain — life and death, clean and unclean, may not be mixed. The rabbinic development of this verse into the elaborate meat-dairy separation of kosher law is a significant exegetical trajectory, though it goes well beyond the text's own statement. The law's canonical repetition (three times in Torah) signals its importance as a boundary marker of Israel's distinctiveness. What is most theologically striking about verse 21 as a whole is that it grounds both laws in the same holiness formula: 'for you are a holy people to the LORD your God.' The kid-in-milk law is not explained further — it is simply anchored in identity. This is the Deuteronomic pattern throughout: the reason for obedience is who you are, not what you understand."
