          "title": "The annual tithe feast — worship as celebratory eating (14:22-26)",
          "body": "The tithe section (vv. 22-29) pivots the chapter from separation (what Israel does not eat) to celebration (what Israel eats before God). The annual tithe of grain, wine, oil, and firstborn animals is to be eaten 'in the presence of the LORD your God, at the place where He chooses to establish His name' (14:23). The meal is sacramental in function — Israel eats before God, not apart from Him. The stated purpose is stunning in its pedagogical candor: 'so that you may learn to fear the LORD your God always' (14:23). Repeated, embodied, annual feasting in God's presence is the divinely ordained means by which Israel learns the fear of God. This is a formation theology: practice shapes disposition. The accommodating provision for distant Israelites (vv. 24-26) is equally remarkable. They may convert the tithe to silver, travel to the central sanctuary, and spend it 'for whatever your heart desires — oxen, sheep, wine, strong drink (*shekhar*), or whatever your soul wishes' (14:26). The inclusion of wine and strong drink in the approved purchase list has surprised many readers; it reflects the festive character of the covenant meal, not a license for excess. The chapter commands joy (*samach*) at the feast — the same verb used throughout Deuteronomy for the great festivals (12:7, 12; 16:11, 14). God's house is a place of feasting and gladness, not austerity. Tim Keller's observation that the Bible's vision of the kingdom is consistently pictured as a feast — not an empty throne room — finds one of its earliest expressions here."
