          "body": "The chapter ends not with the worshiper's feast but with the poor person's provision. Every third year the tithe is redirected from the central sanctuary to the local town gate, where it is deposited for consumption by four named categories of the vulnerable: the Levite (no land inheritance), the alien (no citizenship rights), the orphan (no father to advocate), and the widow (no husband to provide). These four appear together as a fixed formula in Deuteronomy (16:11, 14; 24:19-21; 26:12-13) — they represent the structurally dispossessed within the covenant community. The word *sava* (v. 29 — 'be satisfied') is deliberate: not merely to receive a portion but to eat to full satisfaction. The third-year tithe is a guaranteed provision for their satiation, not a charitable remainder. The promised outcome is covenantal: 'the LORD your God may bless you in all the work of your hand which you do' (14:29). Generosity and divine blessing are bound together within the covenant economy — not as a mechanical transaction but as the expected texture of life within a community where God is Lord of the land and its produce. The New Testament picks up this structure in Acts 2:44-45 and 2 Corinthians 8-9, where Paul grounds the Macedonian collection for Jerusalem's poor in the same covenant logic: God who gives the harvest expects His people to share the surplus with those who have none."
